X-ray crystallography shows that compounds 1 and 2 are isostructural, since they crystallize in the same space group with almost identical cell parameters . Therefore, only the structure of 1 will be discussed in detail. Purple block crystal of 1 was synthesized by heating a mixture of CoSO4·7H2O, Htpba, (NH4)6Mo7O24·4H2O, DMF and distilled water at 160°C for 96h . It was further characterized by elemental analyses, power X-ray diffraction (Figs. S3–4), TG analysis (Figs. S5–6) and IR spectrum (Figs. S7–8). Compound 1 crystallizes in monoclinic system with space group I2/a. There are a half Co(II) ion, a half [Mo2O7]2− anion and a half Htpba ligand in the asymmetric unit of 1 (
). Based on charge balance consideration and bond valence sum calculations , the Co atom exhibits the +II oxidation state and the Mo atom exhibits the +VI oxidation state. The Co atom is coordinated by two nitrogen atoms from two Htpba ligands (Co-N 2.142(2) Å), two carboxylate oxygen atoms from one Htpba ligand and two oxygen atoms from two different [Mo2O7]2− anions (Co-O 2.0719(18)–2.1984(18) Å) to form a distorted octahedron coordination. While the Mo atom exhibits a distorted tetrahedral geometry, coordinated by two terminal oxygen atoms and two μ
2-bridging oxygen atoms [Mo-O 1.716(2)–1.8774(5) Å]. The tetradentate tpba ligand in 1 link three Co atoms. In detail, the carboxylate group chelates with one Co(II) ion, and the two pyridine groups adopt a monodentate coordination mode connecting two Co(II) ions (Scheme S1). The [Mo2O7]2− anions link two Co(II) ions as the pillar.

Based on the above connection modes, the Co ions are connected by tpba ligands to form a 2D metal–organic layer. Topologically, the 2D metal–organic layer of 1 can be simplified as a 3-connected 63-hcb net (a and b). Interestingly, these 2D metal–organic layers are further pillared by [Mo2O7]2− anions to generate a (3,5)-connected 3D hms net with the point symbol of (63)(69.8), in which the tpba ligand and Co atom are respectively simplified as 3- and 5-connected nodes (c and d). Noteworthy, a single 3D network of 1 possesses open 1D channels along the [0 0 1] (ca. 9.001×13.947Å, 
), and [1 0 0] directions (ca. 9.446×16.773Å, 
). Worth mentioning here is that the channels along the [0 0 1] direction are enclosed by the helical chains formed by [Mo2O7]2− anions and 4-(2-(pyridin-4-yl)pyr-idin-4-yl)benzoate groups of tpba ligands bridging the Co atoms (). More intriguingly, a careful examination shows that all the helices in the same individual 3D network exhibit the same chirality (). Moreover, the single 3D network has the large voids to allow the incorporation of another identical 3D network, thus giving a rare twofold interpenetrated hms net (a). To our knowledge, the interpenetrated hms net has never been observed in POM-based hybrid materials prior to this work. An analysis of the interpenetration topology with the TOPOS program  reveals that it belongs to class IIa (two interpenetrated nets are generated only by a full interpenetration symmetry element (inversion center) and the non-translational degree Zn
=2). Despite the interpenetration, PLATON analysis showed that the effective free volume of 1 is 16.8% of the crystal volume, which is occupied by guest water molecules and [(CH3)2NH2]+ cations . To the best of our knowledge, such a 3D microporous interpenetrated framework constructed from metal–organic layers pillared by the polyoxomolybdate anions is still uncommon within POM-based organic–inorganic hybrids .
